I've read every spec, the writer comms doc, and studied your best existing atoms (the nyc_executives anxiety/false_alarm set is the gold standard \'97 David's email spike, Sarah's rescheduled meeting, Michael's unscheduled partner meeting). Here's what I've internalized about what makes those atoms work:\
\
The atom is a held moment, not a summary. David doesn't "feel anxious about emails." His chest tightens before he opens it. The email is about the holiday schedule. The body prepared for termination. The gap between what the body prepared for and what was actually happening \'97 that's the mechanism made visible without naming it.\
\
Named characters with specific, visible detail. Not "a woman" \'97 Sarah. Not "at work" \'97 the client's assistant calls to reschedule. Not "she felt worried" \'97 her hands go cold before she hears the rest of the sentence. The specificity is what makes TTS work. A flat robot voice reading "her hands go cold" lands. A flat robot voice reading "she felt increasingly anxious about the situation" is dead air.\
\
The engine determines the emotional logic. False_alarm atoms show the gap between alarm and reality. Shame atoms show the moment someone sees themselves being seen. Overwhelm atoms show accumulation past capacity. Spiral atoms show recursive thought loops. Each engine has a distinct mechanism, and the atom must embody that mechanism \'97 not describe it, embody it.\
\
No resolution. The atom ends unresolved. Even EMBODIMENT atoms (the "furthest along" role) don't resolve. David waits sixty seconds before opening the email. The waiting proves he has a choice. But the spike still happened. The system still fired. Coexistence, not recovery.\
\
Third person present tense only for STORY. "David's phone buzzes" not "David's phone buzzed." This is non-negotiable and it's what makes TTS land \'97 present tense puts the listener in the room.\
