Step 1: Character bible per persona. Before writing a single atom, I'd build a cast of 8-10 named characters per persona with specific details \'97 job title, physical mannerisms, relationship details, the sensory world they inhabit. NYC executives have glass-walled offices, the 43rd floor, the managing partner. Educators have staff meetings, parent emails, after-school clubs. Healthcare RNs need the ICU, the nurses' station, 12-hour shifts, the beep of monitors. Gen Z professionals need open-plan offices, Slack notifications, standup meetings, imposter syndrome at 24. Gen Alpha students need group chats, the cafeteria, the hallway between classes, parental expectations on a phone screen. These characters recur across engines \'97 David appears in false_alarm AND shame AND spiral \'97 but the engine changes what the moment reveals about the mechanism.\
\
Step 2: Engine-first writing, not topic-first. I'd write all shame atoms across all personas before moving to the next engine. This keeps the engine's emotional logic consistent. Shame is about being seen \'97 the moment of exposure, the heat in the face, the compulsion to hide. If I write shame for educators, then shame for healthcare RNs, then shame for Gen Z, the engine stays sharp. If I write all educator atoms across all engines at once, the engines start bleeding into each other.\
